<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-439-675  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 439 675.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 10 1990 v9 n19 p77(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Senate extends suspension of ethics law provisions.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Congress. SenatePurchasing SystemsAcquisitionLegal IssuesEthics.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Senate Extends Suspension of Ethics Law ProvisionsandM;The Senate has given itself some breathing room on deciding the fate of thegovernment's procurement ethics law, extending for six months a suspension ofthe law's provisions.andM;&quot;This suspension should not be taken by the administration as a sign that theCongress is not concerned about procurement ethics,&quot; said Sen.andP;  Carl Levin(D-Mich.).andP;  &quot;With many of my colleagues, I continue to believe that thesestatutes serve an important purpose, protecting the procurement systemagainst real ethics problems.&quot;andM;Levin introduced the extension last month in an amendment to the defenseauthorization bill.andP;  Its approval means Congress will have until May torevise the law, not Dec. 1, when the suspension was to expire.andM;In a bargain over pay raise legislation last fall, Congress agreed to suspendthe law one year and consider a White House ethics proposal.andP;  The law hadbeen in effect only a few months.andM;Sen.andP;  William V. Roth Jr.andP;  (R-Del.) sponsored the administration's revisionproposal in late June.andP;  The bill, $ 2775, would excise many of the currentlaw's requirements, including the revolving door restrictions,post-employment limitations, gratuity restrictions and contractorcertification requirements.andM;Levin said he was persuaded to offer the amendment because many senators feltthat with the suspension's expiration date pressing, Congress hadinsufficient time to review the proposal or offer its own proposals.andP;  He saidhis Senate Governmental Affairs Subcommittee on Oversight of GovernmentManagement would hold hearings on ethics legislation early next year.andO;</TEXT></DOC>